<HEADLINE>
<P>
CURRENTS: A GUIDE TO THE BEST OF SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA; 
</P>
<P>
HIGH STYLE; 
</P>
<P>
THE NEXT TANGO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVID LASKER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
'EVERYTHING I DESIGN is for what it does, not for its looks," says Stephan 
Copeland, a 30-year-old Montreal-born industrial designer who moved to L.A. so 
he could windsurf at Venice Beach. Unlike the typical desk lamp comprising 
rigid pieces pivoting on a few hinge points, Copeland's Tango lamp has flexible 
steel cables that move in fluid, "organic" fashion. 
</P>
<P>
The design for the Tango was good enough to land Copeland a contract with Flos, 
the high-style Italian lamp manufacturer (he is the first non-Italian to do 
so). Tango also won the prestigious 1989 Institute of Business Designers Bronze 
Award in the portable-lamp category. 
</P>
<P>
List prices for the Tango run: $450 for the table base with halogen bulb, $370 
with fluorescent; $320 for the fluorescent clamp model. 
</P>
<P>
 Available in mid-March at Atelier International Limited, Pacific Design 
Center, 8687 Melrose Ave., Los Angeles, (213) 659-9402. 
</P>
<P>
DAVID LASKER 
</P>
</TEXT>
