<HEADLINE>
<P>
TAIWAN JUDICIAL CHIEF SAYS HE WILL NOT CHALLENGE PRESIDENT LEE IN ELECTIONS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By from Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TAIPEI, Taiwan 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan's judicial chief moved to heal an unprecedented split in the ruling 
Nationalist Party by announcing Friday that he would not challenge President 
Lee Teng-hui in upcoming elections. 
</P>
<P>
Senior government and Nationalist Party officials held emergency sessions last 
week after party elders said they wanted Lin Yang-kang to challenge Lee in 
elections for president and vice president this month. 
</P>
<P>
"People have been thrown into a panic. If there were two teams of candidates in 
the campaign . . . there would be only disagreement and discord," Lin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
