<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO COUNTY DIGEST: CLAIREMONT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two Clairemont men were seriously injured when their light plane crashed in 
rugged mountains east of Ranchita Saturday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
The injured pair were taken to Sharp Memorial Hospital by ambulance after low 
clouds forced a Life Flight helicopter to land at Warner Springs. 
</P>
<P>
The helicopter had been attempting to airlift the two to Palomar Medical Center 
in Escondido. 
</P>
<P>
The pilot, 69-year-old Bill Gray, was reported in serious but stable condition 
Saturday night by Sharp nursing supervisor Melanie Bruce. A 31-year-old 
passenger, who is Gray's roommate, was in critical condition Saturday night 
with head injuries and possible internal injuries, Bruce said. 
</P>
<P>
Gray told hospital officials that he was flying from Borrego Springs to 
Gillespie Field in El Cajon when the plane went down about five miles east of 
Ranchita and a quarter mile north of S22, a county highway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
