<HEADLINE>
<P>
RETURN TO SQUARE ONE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 18.5% of Irvine voters who bothered to go to the polls on Tuesday can't be 
faulted for overwhelmingly rejecting a $57.5-million parks measure. 
</P>
<P>
Dubbed by critics "the Cadillac of bond issues," it was a virtual wish list of 
parks and recreation facilities that was far too ambitious in a time, and in a 
city, where traffic and other more serious problems must share the political 
spotlight. 
</P>
<P>
The measure also contained a troubling provision to pay for maintenance of new 
facilities out of bond money instead of out of the general fund, as is the 
standard municipal practice. 
</P>
<P>
The City Council, which put the measure on the ballot, should use the election 
results as a guide in preparing another measure that would plan for the future 
of this fast-growing planned community on a more modest scale. 
</P>
<P>
The proposal, which needed two-thirds approval, was rejected by an astounding 
76%-24% margin. It had something for everybody, apparently in the hope that 
enough constituencies could be found to put it over the top. 
</P>
<P>
There were to be new parks in Woodbridge, Westpark and Northwood; senior 
citizen and child-care centers; biking, hiking, jogging and equestrian paths; 
gymnasiums; tennis courts and athletic fields, and other park improvements. 
There was even a model farm, a two-acre site complete with a farm building to 
teach visitors about Irvine's agricultural history. 
</P>
<P>
But the price tag for all of this was high: All told, the measure would have 
cost about $300 million when debt service and maintenance and operations costs 
were added to the actual cost of bonds. Each homeowner would have paid $120 a 
year, with mobile homeowners paying half that amount and commercial property 
owners paying significantly more. 
</P>
<P>
Put on the ballot by the City Council after eight months of public hearings, 
the measure had the support of two council members who are usually at odds: 
Mayor Larry Agran, a liberal Democrat, and Republican Councilwoman Sally Anne 
Sheridan. It was opposed by the Irvine Chamber of Commerce, whose members 
objected to increased taxes on their property, and by a group of political 
conservatives who don't much like Agran's style of governing. 
</P>
<P>
But it was given a chance at passage because the city's voters had shown 
themselves to be mavericks on tax issues: Irvine was the only city in Orange 
County to approve Measure M, the half-cent sales tax for transportation, on 
last November's ballot. 
</P>
<P>
While the vote on the parks measure was decisive, it should not be interpreted 
as a signal to give up on planning for the future. It is simply time to go back 
to the drawing board. This time, the council should take into account the 
economic and political realities of Irvine while it continues its tradition 
among suburban communities of providing high-caliber parks for its residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
