<HEADLINE>
<P>
EQUITY SHARING ADVICE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The article by Robert J. Bruss, "Home Equity Sharing Benefits Owner, Renter" 
(Feb. 25), was excellent, with one notable exception: the negative statement 
about the problem arising when the resident co-owner stops making the monthly 
payments. 
</P>
<P>
In the real estate investors program, we call the co-owners the "buyer" and 
"investor." 
</P>
<P>
The buyers start with no equity and earn their 50% share of the equity increase 
over five years or 60 payments. If they default or have to move before five 
years, their share is prorated. Therefore, even in a default the buyers don't 
lose everything. 
</P>
<P>
We establish an open holding escrow to collect the monthly payments including a 
requirement of depositing one month payment in advance. The holding escrow also 
retains a signed grant deed from the buyer to the investor. If a problem is 
developing, the escrow officer will know one month before that payment is due. 
</P>
<P>
HERMAN W. PASS 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
<P>
Pass is president of Real Equity Investors Inc. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA031190-0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 187912 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
March 11, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Real Estate; Part K; Page 21; Column 1; Real Estate Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
